<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-07-24T11:28:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-07-24T11:28:00-05:00" n="410" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d410">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72/1940: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Vice President</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Marshall</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Indianapolis, Ind.</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-07-24T10:28:00-06:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">July 24, 1915—10:28 a. m.</hi>
                                </date>
                                <lb/> [Received 11:41 a. m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Congratulations.<note n="39" xml:id="d410fn1">i. e., on the note to
                                Germany of July 21, 1915, printed in <ref target="frus1915Supp#pg_480">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1915, supp., p.
                                    480</ref>.</note> You have said it. Follow with note to England
                            defining the American idea and we are impregnable.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Thos. R. Marshall</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>